      "english_close": "This jīva is not absolutely different from Śrī Puruṣottama, nor again absolutely non-different; rather, it is a part of the supreme self. For scripture says, 'this one is indeed a part of the supreme.' And a 'part' is indeed to be understood as being of the form of a power: 'it is the power of the supreme'; 'the jīva is a limited power, not independent' - so says scripture.",
      "preserved_terms": [
        {
          "term_iast": "aṃśa",
          "first_use_gloss": "(roughly: part, here a dependent power-expression rather than a severed fragment)"
        },
        {
          "term_iast": "śakti",
          "first_use_gloss": "(roughly: power or potency)"
        }
      ],
      "why_this_passage": "This is the cleanest recoverable statement of Śrīnivāsa's mature bhedābheda: the jīva is neither sheer otherness nor sheer identity, but a dependent power-as-part of the supreme. It fairly represents his position because it occurs exactly where he explains the Brahma-Sūtra on aṃśatva, not in a later caricature of an opponent.",
